Detect Cycle in Singly Linked List — Floyd’s Tortoise & Hare

Goal: Determine if a linked list contains a cycle.
Approach: Two pointers

slow moves 1 step; fast moves 2 steps.
If they ever meet → cycle exists. If fast hits null → no cycle.


Why it works: In a cyclic loop, the faster pointer eventually “laps” the slower one, guaranteeing a meeting point.
Complexity:

Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)


Edge Cases:

Empty list (head == null) → false
Single node without cycle → false
Single node pointing to itself → true


Pitfalls to avoid:

Always check fast != null && fast.next != null before advancing fast = fast.next.next.






public class Solution {
    public boolean hasCycle(ListNode head) {
       ListNode slow = head;
       ListNode fast = head;
       while(fast!=null && fast.next!=null){
        slow = slow.next;
        fast = fast.next.next;
        if(slow==fast){
            return true;
        }
       }
       return false;
    }
}
        
    
